%%TITLE
Clinical characteristics of Japanese oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma positive for human papillomavirus infection.
%%ABSTRACT
Human papillomavirus (HPV)-related oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OPSCC) is considered to be a distinct entity in Japan. The combination of both HPV-DNA sequencing analysis and immunohistochemistry (IHC) for p16(INK4A) is useful to discriminate the OPSCC patients with a better prognosis from other cases, especially in the advanced stage. Surgical treatment is recommended for HPV-negative advanced cancer.The number of HPV-related OPSCCs has been increasing worldwide. However, the incidence and prognostic significance of this cancer in Japan have not yet been fully elucidated.Seventy-seven Japanese patients with OPSCC were enrolled in this study. The prevalence of HPV-DNA was assessed by PCR and sequencing. The expression of p16(INK4A) and p53 was examined by IHC. The clinicopathological parameters and disease-specific survival were analyzed for HPV-positive and -negative patients.HPV-DNA was detected in 32 patients. Thirty-four patients were p16(INK4A)-positive by IHC. The patients who were positive for HPV infection were significantly younger. Furthermore, in the stage III or IV cases, the 3-year disease-specific survival of the HPV infection-positive group was significantly better than that of the HPV-negative group. Surgical treatment was demonstrated to lead to a good prognosis for the patients with HPV-negative advanced cancer.
%%MATERIAL AND METHODS
Patients and lesions
A total of 87 patients with OPSCC treated between 1999 and 2011 at the Medical Hospital of Tokyo Medical and Dental University were enrolled in this study. This study was performed in accordance with the World Medical Association, the Declaration of Helsinki, 2008. The ethics committees of Tokyo Medical and Dental University approved the proto- cols, and each patient provided their informed consent to participate in this study. Ten patients did not agree to participate in the present study, and the remaining 77 patients whose specimens were available for analysis were analyzed.
The clinicopathological parameters, such as the patient’s gender and age, smoking and drinking habits, TNM classiﬁcation, treatment regimens, and survival were collected for the analyses.
Specimens obtained by surgery or incisional biopsy were quickly frozen and stored at 80oC for sequenc- ing analysis. In cases where fresh specimens could not be obtained, formalin-ﬁxed, parafﬁn-embedded
(FFPE) tissue was used for the sequencing analysis. Hematoxylin and eosin (H&E)-stained sections were reviewed, and one FFPE block that included a rep- resentative area of the primary tumor was selected. Several sections 4 mm thick were cut from the FFPE lesions and used for IHC. The histopathological eva- luations, including IHC, were performed by two medical pathologists (T.I. and H.K.) individually, without information about the clinical outcome. In cases where a different result was obtained, the pathologists re-evaluated the specimens and made a consensus diagnosis after discussion.
HPV-DNA detection by PCR and sequencing analyses
DNA was extracted from fresh tissue samples using a QIAmp DNA mini kit (Qiagen, Venlo The Nether- lands). DNA was extracted from FFPE samples using a QIAmp DNA FFPE Tissue Kit (Qiagen). PCR analysis of the extracted DNA samples was performed using four primers, including: 5¢-cgtccmarrggawact- gatc-3¢, 5¢-gcmcagggwcataayaatgg-3¢, 5¢-ttatcwtatgcc- caytgtaccat-3¢, and 5¢-atgttaatwsagccwccaaaatt-3¢ (where ‘M’ means A or C, ‘R’ means A or G, ‘W’ means A or T, ‘Y’ means T or C, and ‘S’ means G or C). Subsequently, a sequencing analysis was per- formed to determine whether the HPV gene was present or not The identiﬁcation of HPV-DNA was achieved by determining the size of the PCR ampliﬁcation product by gel electrophoresis. The obtained sequences were compared with documented virus sequences that were available in GenBank using the BLAST program The HPV type was then determined based on these comparisons.
IHC
We used monoclonal antibodies against p16INK4A (clone E6H4, CINtec, Basel, Switzerland, diluted 1:1) and p53 (p53, clone DO-7, Novocastra, New- castle upon Tyne, UK, diluted 1:1000) for the IHC studies. The antigen retrieval was performed using an autoclave at 121oC for 20 min. Subsequently, all sections were incubated with a primary antibody at its working dilution at 4oC for 24 h. The sections were stained to detect each antigen using a Vectastain ABC Immunoperoxidase kit (Vector Laboratories, Burlington, CA, USA). The sections were incubated in 3,3’-diaminobenzidine for 10 min, which stained the antigen brown, and then were counterstained with Mayer’s hematoxylin.

HPV infection status
The HPV infection status was regarded as positive when either HPV was detected or p16INK4A positivity was demonstrated, while negative HPV infection

status was regarded as present when neither HPV nor p16INK4A was demonstrated.
Treatment regimen
We mainly chose surgery and radiation therapy for the patients with OPSCC from 1999 through 2006. Since 2007, TPF-based neoadjuvant chemotherapy (NAC), which combines three agents, docetaxel (DOC), cis- platin (CDDP) and 5-ﬂuorouracil (5-FU), has been administered to the patients with OPSCC. Patients who achieved a complete response (CR) or partial response (PR) underwent concurrent chemora- diotherapy (CCRT) with TPF-based NAC. The patients and their families were thoroughly advised regarding the advantages and disadvantages of these basic treatment strategies, as well as the expected therapeutic outcomes. The choice of treatment was determined based on the patient’s preference and at the surgeon’s discretion.
The NAC regimen consisted of the administration of DOC on day 1, followed by 120 h of continuous infusion of 5-FU (days 1–5) with CDDP administra- tion on day 4. The doses administered were as fol- lows: DOC, 60 mg/m2; CDDP, 70 mg/m2; and 5-FU, 750 mg/m2/day. During CCRT, these doses were: DOC, 50 mg/m2; CDDP, 60 mg/m2; and 5-FU, 600 mg/m2/day. The dose of radiation was 60 Gy, and the chemotherapy generally involved two courses. The other criteria have been reported previously by Katori and Tsukuda
Statistical analysis
For the statistical evaluations, we used the generalized Wilcoxon test, Kaplan–Meier product limit method, log-rank test, Fisher’s exact test, and a Cox propor- tional hazards regression analysis. A value of p < 0.05 was considered to be statistically signiﬁcant. The StatMate III statistical software program for Windows (ATMS, Tokyo, Japan) and the EZR soft- ware program (Free Soft, Saitama, Japan) were used to perform all statistical analyses.
